  <discussion>The marginal teeth of the leaves of Elodium blandowii, especially proximally and medially, are sharply dentate-serrate, sharper than those of E. elodioides, whereas the margins of E. paludosum are nearly entire, lacking teeth. The papillae are narrow and elevated and, especially on branch leaves, antrorsely curved like those in Echinophyllum, but much more delicate. The length of the seta of E. blandowii (4–6 cm) is more than twice that of E. elodioides or E. paludosum (both 2–2.8 cm) and the capsules are larger (3–4 mm in E. blandowii, 2–2.5 mm in both E. elodioides and E. paludosum).</discussion>
